05504nam a22008415i 9780812298321DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1302166682  a97808122983217 a10.9783/97808122983212doi  a(DE-B1597)590732  a(OCoLC)1301546294  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a780/.082qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aBude, Tekla, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSonic Bodies :bText, Music, and Silence in Late Medieval England /cTekla Bude. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b11 bw halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSound in History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Writing Sonic Bodies -- tChapter 1. Musica Celestis and Canor: Angelic Song in Speculative Music Theory and Rollean Mysticism -- tChapter 2. Touching Music: Walter Hilton, Angels’ Song, and Synaesthesia -- tChapter 3. Attending to The Boke of Margery Kempe -- tChapter 4. Music, Amicitia, and Carthusian Mystical Diaries -- tChapter 5. Piers Plowman, the Sound-Object, and the Singing Community -- tChapter 6. Disability, Music, and Chaucer’s Advental Bodies -- tCoda -- tAppendix. A Short Exposition of the Manuscripts in Chapter 4 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the body when it performs music? And what, conversely, is music as it reverberates through or pours out of a performing body? Tekla Bude starts from a simple premise—that music requires a body to perform it—to rethink the relationship between music, matter, and the body in the late medieval period.Progressing by way of a series of case studies of texts by Richard Rolle, Walter Hilton, Margery Kempe, Geoffrey Chaucer, William Langland, and others, Bude argues that writers thought of "music" and "the body" not as separate objects or ontologically prior categories, but as mutually dependent and historically determined processes that called each other into being in complex and shifting ways. For Bude, these "sonic bodies" are often unexpected, peculiar, even bizarre, and challenge our understanding of their constitutive parts.Building on recent conversations about embodiment and the voice in literary criticism and music theory, Sonic Bodies makes two major interventions across these fields: first, it broadens the definitional ambits and functions of both "music" and "the body" in the medieval period; and second, it demonstrates how embodiment and musicality are deeply and multiply intertwined in medieval writing. Compelling literary subjects, Bude argues, are literally built out of musical situations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEngland. 0aKörper. 0aMusik. 0aMusiktheorie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLangland.  aLiterature.  aMedieval English literaturepoetry.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aMiddle English.  aMusic, embodiment, mysticism, Richard Rolle, Chaucer, Piers Plowman, Margery Kempe.  aWalter Hilton.  adevotionals.  afourteenth fifteenth sixteenth century.  aliturgical religious studies.  amusicology.  aperformance disability studies.  aphenomenology.  aqueer theory.  asynaesthesia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAG